{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 13:24:14.371654", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnostic report — current network state\n\nExecutive summary\n- There is a clear connectivity anomaly between the 20.200.0.0/24 “backend” network (backend_web_0..2, load_balancer:eth1) and the rest of the network (10.200.0.0/24: web servers, dns_server, dhcp_server, routers).\n- Backend hosts (20.200.0.2–.4) can reach each other and the load_balancer, and the load_balancer itself can reach 10.200.0.0/24. However, packets sourced from backend hosts to 10.200.0.0/24 are not getting replies — pings from backend hosts to DNS and web servers fail with 100% packet loss.\n- Root cause (most likely): the 20.200.0.0/24 network is not advertised/known in the OSPF routing domain (no route to 20.200.0.0 on FRR routers), producing asymmetric routing / missing return route for traffic from 10.200.0.0/24 back to 20.200.0.0/24.\n\nKey observations and evidence\n1) Reachability matrix (summary of ping tests)\n   - Multiple tests show 100% loss when backend hosts attempt to reach 10.200.0.0/24:\n     - backend_web_2 -> dns_server (10.200.0.2): 100% loss\n     - backend_web_1 -> dns_server: 100% loss\n     - backend_web_0 -> dns_server: 100% loss\n     - backend_web_1/2 -> web_server_0..3 (10.200.x.x): 100% loss\n     - dhcp_server -> backend_web_2: 100% loss\n   - backend hosts can reach each other and the load_balancer:\n     - backend_web_X -> backend_web_Y: OK (0% loss)\n     - backend_web_X -> load_balancer (20.200.0.1): OK (0% loss)\n   - load_balancer -> dns_server: OK (0% loss)\n   - Web servers (10.200.0.x) can reach dns_server and load_balancer (OK).\n\n   These results indicate packets from 20.200 → 10.200 are sent but replies are not returned to the 20.200 hosts (or are dropped on the way back).\n\n2) Host network configurations\n   - backend_web_0..2:\n     - IPs in 20.200.0.0/24, default route via 20.200.0.1 (load_balancer).\n     - Example: backend_web_2 eth0: 20.200.0.4/24, default via 20.200.0.1.\n   - load_balancer:\n     - eth1: 20.200.0.1/24 (backend side)\n     - eth0: 10.200.0.7/24 (server farm side)\n     - net.ipv4.ip_forward = 1 (forwarding enabled)\n   - dns_server:\n     - 10.200.0.2/24, default via 10.200.0.1 (server_access_router).\n\n   Interpretation: Backend hosts use the load_balancer as their gateway. The load_balancer has interfaces on both 20.200 and 10.200 nets and is capable of forwarding traffic.\n\n3) Router/OSPF state\n   - server_access_router FRR running-config (showing advertised networks):\n     - network 10.200.0.0/24 area 0\n     - networks in 172.16.0.x\n     - No mention of 20.200.0.0/24 in FRR config on server_access_router.\n   - core routers’ routing tables show routes for 10.200.0.0/24, but none show 20.200.0.0/24 being learned/advertised via OSPF.\n   - Conclusion: the routing domain (FRR/OSPF) does not have a route for 20.200.0.0/24.\n\nDiagnosis / root cause\n- The backend subnet (20.200.0.0/24) is isolated from the network-level routing domain: it is not being advertised into OSPF, so other routers do not have a route to reach 20.200.0.0/24.\n- The load_balancer forwards outbound traffic from backend hosts to 10.200.0.0/24 (it is connected to both networks), so backend→10.200 traffic reaches destination hosts. However, replies from 10.200 hosts are routed according to their routing tables (via server_access_router and OSPF). Because routers do not have a route for 20.200.0.0/24, reply packets do not reach the load_balancer/backend hosts (asymmetric routing / missing return path).\n- Evidence supporting asymmetric/missing return path:\n  - load_balancer and many 10.200 hosts can ping each other (OK).\n  - backend hosts can ping load_balancer and peer backends (OK).\n  - backend hosts cannot ping 10.200 hosts or dns_server (100% packet loss) even though load_balancer has forwarding enabled and connectivity to 10.200.\n  - FRR/OSPF config and routing tables lack 20.200 advertisement.\n\nLocalized faulty/impacted components\n- Affected (connectivity-impacting):\n  - backend_web_0, backend_web_1, backend_web_2 (20.200.0.2–.4): cannot reach 10.200.0.0/24 services (dns, web servers) from their IPs — inbound responses fail.\n  - The 20.200.0.0/24 network as a whole (from perspective of the OSPF domain) — not present/advertised.\n- Non-faulty or working:\n  - load_balancer: has both IPs and IP forwarding enabled; it has local connectivity to both sides (it can reach dns_server and backends).\n  - web_server_0..3, dns_server, dhcp_server: can reach each other and load_balancer (10.200 side OK).\n  - FRR routers: OSPF appears operational for advertised networks (10.200 and 172.16 networks) but they do not know 20.200.0.0/24.\n\nImpact / service implications\n- Backend nodes (20.200) are effectively unreachable from the wider network (10.200 and elsewhere) except via the load_balancer itself, because routers lack a route to 20.200.\n- Any service or management traffic that requires return-path reachability to backend IPs (20.200 addresses) from other subnets will fail.\n- DNS queries from backends to dns_server are failing (backend -> dns 100% loss), which may prevent backend hosts from resolving names (backends cannot reach DNS).\n- The load_balancer, being on both subnets, may still be able to proxy/health-check backends locally; front-end service (web99.local) might appear functional depending on how load_balancer handles traffic (but we did not test application-level behavior). However, network-level reachability to backend IPs from other network devices is broken.\n\nTests performed (tools & outputs used)\n- get_reachability (full ping matrix) — revealed numerous 100% loss cases from 20.200→10.200 and OK for backend↔backend and backend↔load_balancer.\n- get_host_net_config on:\n  - backend_web_0/1/2 — confirmed 20.200 addressing and default via 20.200.0.1.\n  - load_balancer — confirmed dual-homed (10.200.0.7 and 20.200.0.1) and ip_forward = 1 (checked via exec_shell).\n  - dns_server — confirmed 10.200.0.2 and default via 10.200.0.1.\n- frr_show_running_config on server_access_router — shows only 10.200 networks advertised; no 20.200.\n\nAdditional notes / caveats\n- Some host-to-host reachability entries involving host_1_1_1_1 and host_2_1_1_1 returned “unknown” in the automated matrix — those client hosts were not probed successfully by the reachability tool in this run, so their state is not conclusively measured here.\n- This report avoids proposing remediations (per instructions) — but the data strongly points to missing route advertisement for 20.200.0.0/24 (not present in FRR/OSPF), producing the observed asymmetric routing and packet loss.\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- Show the FRR OSPF neighbor and LSDB state on core routers to further confirm absence of 20.200 advertisement.\n- Run traceroutes from a backend host to dns_server and from dns_server to a backend host to capture the asymmetric path.\n- Inspect load_balancer iptables/nat rules to confirm it is not NAT-ing traffic (if you want evidence whether source NAT is in use).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 14524, "output_tokens": 4564, "total_tokens": 19088, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 13952}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2624}}}
